Reference-contexts: The system is based on the framework of a low bit rate hybrid-DCT system called SIM3 [2], but where the DCT residual coder is replaced with a matching pursuit coder. This coder uses the matching pursuit algorithm <ref> [4] </ref> to decompose each motion residual image over a dictionary of separable 2-D Gabor functions. The resulting system was shown to perform well on low motion sequences at 10 and 20 kbit/s. <p> Each component structure in the summation is called an "atom." The primary task of the residual coder is to match the dictionary structures to the residual image and thus reduce it to a representative set of atoms. This is accomplished using a multi-stage algorithm called matching pursuits <ref> [4] </ref>. At each stage, the dictionary is searched for the structure which best matches the current stage residual image in an inner product sense. In theory, each of the dictionary structures should be compared to the residual image at all possible pixel-resolution locations.
